Here is an example implementation using `jsonwebtoken` library:

```javascript
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

async function authenticateToken(token: string): Promise<any> {
  try {
    const decodedClaims = awaitjwt.verify(
      token,
      process.env.JWT_SECRET || 'secret'
    );

    return { ...decodedClaims };
  } catch(error) {
   throw new Error(`Invalid or expired JWT`);
 }

}

// Usage:
try{
 let result = authenticateUser(authenticateToken(process.env.AUTH_TOKEN));
 console.log(result);
}catch(err){
console.error("Error:", err.message)
}
```

In this code snippet we're defining two functions - one that decodes the given JWT into its corresponding object with claim information (`decode`) and another where it verifies whether our provided JWT corresponds to any existing authentication data stored at `process.env.JWT_SECRET`. The `.verify()` method from the `jsonwebtoken` module takes care about both verification logic as well as handling invalid/missing values.

When you run your script above on some environment variables like "AUTH_TOKEN" set correctly, then when you call either `/token`, "/login", etc., there should be no error messages indicating missing/deleted secret value which makes sure authenticity has been maintained properly by all parties involved here!

