To create a simple dark/light theme switcher for your React app with TailWindCSS, you can follow these steps:

1. Install necessary dependencies:
   ```
npm install --save-dev tailwindcss@^2.0.3 react-transition-group @tailwindlabs/closet @types/react @emotion/react +emotion-emphasize -S```

2\. Set up the basic structure of your `App.js` file by importing required components and hooks.

```javascript
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import {
  Switch,
  Route,
} from "react-router-dom";
import styled from '@emotion/styled';

const Wrapper = styled.div`
display: flex;
flex-direction: column;

${props => props.theme === true ? `
justify-content: center; 
align-items: stretch;  
height: auto;
padding-top: ${themeLevel * 4}px;}

color:${({ color }) =>
    ({ lightTheme }).darkMode && `${themeColor}` || ({"default": "#fff", "trueDark": color}.red ?? red)}
font-size:` +
      (${{ fontSize }}) };
`;
export default function App() {

// Your routes here...
}
```
Note that we set our component to have an explicit style definition via `.styled`. This will allow us use variables like `style={{ background: '#f5a86b'}}`, but not as inline styles within JSX tags (`{{...}}`). 

Now let's define how it looks when toggling between dark and lighter modes based on colors or other properties.

For simplicity sake assume both states share some common attributes such as padding, border radius etc...

**Step-1:** Define separate state types for different themes/colors where appropriate  

e.g., RedButton.propTypes={background:"#FFC97A"}

** Step-2**: Use conditional rendering logic inside `<Switch>` tag according to current theme/color value passed into parent render method through prop object. In this example below we'll just change margin values depending upon which theme is active:

```jsx
switch(props.mode){
case "light":
 return (
 <Wrapper>
     // Styles applied only during light-theme condition    
 </wrapper>

 case("dark"):
return(
<Wrapper css={{
marginTop:"calc(1rem*#{$borderRadius})",
marginLeft:"-#{themeMargin}",
}}>
</>)

}

else{
throw new Error(`Invalid Theme Mode!`);
 }
)
}else{
 throw new TypeError('This should never happen');
 }

});
```.

Here `{#$}`, `$BorderRadius`, and $themeMargins refer to custom utility functions defined elsewhere if needed.

Remember, always validate input data before applying styling so avoid any unexpected side effects due to invalid inputs!

Finally remember also about [Emmet](https://github.com/emmetjs/editor), Emmitting HTML/CSS elements directly without having them rendered yet ensures consistent behavior across browser versions since version 1.x. It might be useful especially for complex transitions/animations involving multiple divs/components dynamically added later.

