To improve performance and scalability of your website, consider the following optimization strategies in your NGINX (1.x) or NGinx v4.x/NgRx 2.x /v3.x/nginx.conf files:

```nginx
http {
    server_tokens off;

    # Set worker threads based on CPU count.
    workers_min_size = 5;
    WorkersPerChild { min_spare_workers=8 max_s pare_workers={max_children=60};
                    }

    access_log /var/log/ngx_http_access.log;
}

# Max requests per connection setting is recommended to avoid overwhelming backend servers:
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=myreqs:10m rate=$proxy_connect_back burst=1";

events {

        use epoll_event;

       default_backend mybackend;

}
```

Here's how these settings can be applied:

*   `workers` directive sets up a pool of worker processes that will process incoming connections concurrently.

*     `$worker_processes` variable controls the number of concurrent worker tasks being executed by one NGNix instance at once while running multiple applications simultaneously through multi-processes (`forkserver`). This ensures maximum utilization without overloading single-threaded instances like Redis which may not handle such large volumes well under load conditions.

By adjusting the above directives according to actual application requirements, it becomes easier for web developers to ensure their websites run smoothly even during peak hours when numerous users request data from them within short intervals.

Note - These changes apply only if using either NGinxs version below V7.x.XV (or later versions). For older NGInyx releases prior to this point, refer directly to [official documentation](https://docs.nginx.com/nginx-ingress-controller/configuration/#configuration-options-for-instances), where specific options relevant here might vary slightly but still follow best practices guidelines as mentioned earlier due to compatibility reasons between newer NGI Xinsser controllers & different NGIx versions used today including those released after current official NGIX docs release date. 

